<dl id="n30174e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n30" href="#n30174e">N30 (VI.B.22)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n30all.htm#n30174e"> 174(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> tongue / somniloquence</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Lastly, the dream overflow may be into the speech centres in the frontal lobes. The content of the dream may be such that it tends to induce words to be spoken, so that the cerebral speech centres are energized. The term <mark>somniloquence</mark> is sometimes used for <mark>talking</mark> in sleep. <small> D. F. Fraser-Harris, <a name="FHMS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FHMS"><cite title="source">Morpheus, or: The Future of Sleep</cite></a> (1928) 66</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
